This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing and conversation modeling. Additionally, the use of distributed embeddings and sequence-to-sequence models are common techniques in this field. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the paper discusses the use of neural networks for generating responses in a conversational setting. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category as the paper involves training models to learn and generate responses based on personas and interactions between speakers. 

cs.SD (Sound) is less likely but still possible as the paper deals with modeling speaking styles and interactions between speakers. 

Finally, cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is also a possibility as the paper involves the use of neural networks for generating responses in a conversational setting.
